The intersection of sets A and B, denoted as A ∩ B, is the set of all elements that are common to both A and B. 

A = {1, 2, 3, 4, 5}
B = {2, 4, 6, 8, 10}

A ∩ B = {2, 4}

Now, we need to prove that the resulting set {2, 4} is a subset of both A and B. A set C is a subset of a set D (denoted as C ⊆ D) if every element of C is also an element of D.

For set A:
2 ∈ A and 4 ∈ A, so {2, 4} ⊆ A.

For set B:
2 ∈ B and 4 ∈ B, so {2, 4} ⊆ B.

Therefore, the intersection of sets A and B, {2, 4}, is a subset of both A and B.
